related.description: The Lakers' Shaquille O'Neal left Sacramento with a spoiled souvenir of his 20,000th career point -- someone scribbled an insulting expletive on the ball used when he reached the milestone.
related.title: Vandal scribbles expletive on O'Neal's ball

article.headline: Celtics have no answer for 'unfrontable' Shaq
article.linkText: Shaq overwhelms mismatched Celtics for 48 points
article.story:
LOS ANGELES (AP) -- The Boston Celtics tried to defend Shaquille O'Neal by positioning their center in front of him. It didn't work.
O'Neal

Taking lob passes from his teammates, the Lakers center scored 48 points and had 20 rebounds Friday night to lead Los Angeles to a 104-96 victory over the Celtics. "The guys got me the ball in scoring position, above the rim. If I can get the ball like that every time, most of the time I will score because I have the strength and the power to just go up,'' O'Neal said. "They were fronting me, and I've always considered myself 'unfrontable.' My guys were looking for me and I was feeling it. I should have had 60, but I missed a couple of free throws. O'Neal, who went 19-of-24 from the floor and 10-of-19 from the line, spent most of the night overpowering Tony Battie and Mark Blount in the middle. The 7-foot-1, 340-pound Lakers center outweighs the 6-11 Battie by 100 pounds, and the 7-foot Blount by 90 pounds. "We were fronting on him and they were throwing the ball over the top,'' Battie said. "We were going to make him beat us and keep everyone else at bay. It worked for three quarters, but down the stretch they pulled away.'' Boston coach Jim O'Brien said, "Just too much Mr. O'Neal. We played a tough game, scored well, but just could not stop the big fella. We fronted the post because if you play behind him, he will just dominate you anyway. We just did not have an answer for him.''
" We've had many conversations before, great conversations, some that I'll never forget, some that'll last with me forever. I wish I could have had the same relationship with Mr. Chamberlain. "
— Shaquille O'Neal, on his relationship with Celtics legend Bill Russell
NBA Hall of Famer Bill Russell, the former Celtics center who had a decade of classic matchups against the Lakers' Wilt Chamberlain, watched from a front-row seat on the baseline near the Lakers' bench. "Bill Russell's probably one of the greatest centers to ever play the game. He was there watching me, so I wanted to put on a show,'' O'Neal said. "We've had many conversations before, great conversations, some that I'll never forget, some that'll last with me forever. "I wish I could have had the same relationship with Mr. Chamberlain.'' Lakers coach Phil Jackson said O'Neal has been playing well, and that he is in good shape now to play "night in and night out.'' "When I told him to tell me when he was ready in the fourth quarter, he said he was born ready,'' Jackson said. The win was the Lakers' first over the Celtics in their last four meetings. Kobe Bryant, who scored 40 points or more in nine consecutive games earlier this season, again deferred to O'Neal, taking just 11 shots and scoring 13 points against the Celtics. Antoine Walker led Boston with 25 points, but scored just five after halftime as the Celtics lost their third in a row. J.R. Bremer added 23 points and Paul Pierce 21. The Lakers, who trailed by 13 just before halftime, took their first lead on Rick Fox's 3-pointer that put them up 64-63 with 5:14 remaining in the third quarter. They stayed in front the rest of the way, building their first double-digit lead on Devean George's 21-footer that made it 81-71 with 10:22 left. The Celtics got no closer than five after that. The Lakers were coming off a 107-99 defeat by the Kings at Sacramento on Thursday night.

Game notes
O'Neal left Sacramento with a spoiled souvenir of his 20,000th career point. Someone scribbled an insulting expletive on the ball used when he got the milestone basket. The unknown culprit got to the ball sometime after Lakers public relations director John Black had grabbed it just before halftime. O'Neal, who was booed by the Sacramento crowd at halftime when his accomplishment was announced, said he hoped no one connected with the Kings was responsible. "I hope the Maloof family (Kings' owners Gavin and Joe Maloof) doesn't condone this kind of action,'' said O'Neal, the 28th NBA player to reach the plateau. "But this is one thing I won't forget, and I'll see you soon.'' ... Seated close to Russell in the first row was former Boston guard Bill Sharman, who coached the Lakers to the 1971-72 NBA title.
